properties.title: Voces de la Frontera
properties.description: kiramke2 posted a photo: Milwaukee, WI 5/1/11 This May Day, 60,000+ people marched in solidarity for Immigrant and Worker Rights from the south side through downtown Milwaukee to Veteran's Park, chanting "Si se puede" - "Yes we can!" Most represent Milwaukee's hispanic community, which is largely voiceless in government and disproportionately affected by current proposed legislation.

properties.title: My Dream
properties.description: kiramke posted a photo: Milwaukee, WI 5/1/11 Protest day 77 On May Day, at least 60,000 people gathered to march from the south side of Milwaukee to Veteran's park at the lakefront, in solidarity for immigrant and worker rights. This march was organized by Voces de la Frontera, a great organization that supports immigrant and low-income workers in the area. After census results were posted, Milwaukee was once again listed as the #1 most segregated city in the country. So when we discuss cuts to support in our community, elimination of ESL teaching, limited transit, voter residency, and many more bills, these changes disproportionately affect our citizens by neighborhood and thus by racial group. In addition, our state legislature is considering a bill similar to Arizona's that targets immigrants. I think people forget that their local community doesn't represent everyone else in their state. My hope is that they will begin to think not just about how the laws will affect them, but how they will affect others.

properties.title: Alterra Prospect
properties.description: johndecember posted a photo: Posted for MKE Cafes. A Pattern Language: Towns, Buildings, Construction by Christopher Alexander, Sara Ishikawa, Murray Silverstein See section 88, "Street Cafe," p. 437: "The street cafe provides a unique setting, special to cities: a place where people can sit lazily, legitimately, be on view, and watch the world go by. Encourage local cafes to spring up in each neighborhood. Make them intimate places, with several rooms, open to a busy path, where people can sit with coffee or a drink and watch the world go by. Build the front of the cafe so that a set of tables stretch out of the cafe, right into the street."

properties.title: Former supermarket (Milwaukee, WI)
properties.description: Andrew T... posted a photo: Milwaukee's West Capitol Drive segment is lined with interesting mid-century signs and buildings. If I lived there, I'd take pictures of all of them. Exhibit A: Although it may not be obvious, the front of this store is finished off in deep red porcelain-enamel tile. Combined with the out-tilted glass and multi-level roof, it makes for a very eye-catching building! According to public records, it was built in 1953. It's anyone's guess what this building originally housed, though. Perhaps I'll be able to consult a stack of old Milwaukee directories eventually...

properties.title: Unocal 76 station (Greenfield, WI)
properties.description: Andrew T... posted a photo: While poking around metro Milwaukee trying to find my way back to the Interstate, I found this. Most 76 gas stations in the midwest converted to Citgo in 1997, and it's rare to find any trace left of them now. The "Unocal" sign is doubly uncommon because even on the west coast where 76 still operates, Topco and Conoco did not retain the rights to the Unocal name. Not that I have anything good to say about Unocal as a company, but these graphics are scarce indeed. Judging by the "Service" sign over the bays, this also did time as a Mobil station at some point. Compare.
